Hey, friends, let me tell you, the most mind-blowing city in the world —— Chongqing! Just imagine a magical maze with 32 million people, looking like it jumped straight out of a cyberpunk video game! Yeah, this super city has more people than the entire population of Canada, yet it’s like a hidden gem in the southwest of China!
First off, the architecture here is just insane! Ancient stilt houses cling to cliffs, while modern skyscrapers pierce the clouds, and those huge red bridges stretch across the two rivers like dragons. The colors and scale are like someone turned a fantasy painter’s sketchbook into reality! The infrastructure is even more exaggerated — roads winding through the mountains, subways diving into tunnels, escalators climbing entire hillsides, and even Google Maps gives up on navigation!
The most amazing thing is that such a huge city is still off the tourist radar. Unlike Shanghai or Hong Kong, getting here isn’t easy. But trust me, the bumpy flights and winding mountain roads are totally worth it! Why? Let me break it down for you:
History: This place was a major trading hub 3,000 years ago, and you can still wander through the same alleyways that ancient emperors walked.
Food: It’s the birthplace of Chongqing hotpot! With its boiling beef tallow base and numbingly spicy Sichuan peppercorns, you’ll get a mix of pain and pleasure as you dip the freshest ingredients into the pot!
Nightlife（06:12:51）: At night, the Hongyadong area looks like a fairy-tale cliff palace, with neon lights dancing on the river. And the rooftop bars? The night views are simply amazing!
But what makes Chongqing truly unique is its “chaotic aesthetics.” Old teahouses sit next to luxury malls, and monkeys wander in the forests beside skyscrapers. You might just have taken a river crossing cable car, and after passing through a tunnel, you’re suddenly in a bookstore, and then in the blink of an eye, you’re in a bamboo forest. The city is like playing hide-and-seek with you, with surprises around every corner!
So, if you’re tired of cookie-cutter cities and want to experience an adventure that feels like crossing dimensions, Chongqing is definitely the top choice! Remember to wear good shoes, bring your curiosity, and pack some antacids —— because the hotpot is no joke!

29:42 In Chongqing, it's very common to have height differences of several or even dozens of floors like that, especially in Yuzhong District. Often, you might think you're on the first floor, but in another direction, you could be on the 20th floor. Or you might think you're on the 10th floor, but in another direction, you could be seven floors underground. The truth is, you're always in the same place—it's just that the terrain in Chongqing is so rugged that the same location can appear as completely different floors depending on the direction. Locals in Chongqing have long since adapted to and become accustomed to this. Chongqing is a mountain city, one of the few mega-cities in the world built on rugged mountainous terrain. It's a highly three-dimensional city. Chinese people often call Chongqing an '8D city.' 
There's a content creator on Bilibili called '重庆磊少' (Chongqing Lei Shao). He used to be a real estate agent in Chongqing, and many of his videos showcase the interiors of properties that are for rent or sale, mainly in Yuzhong District and other districts in the city center. These videos vividly demonstrate the unique rugged terrain of the city, the winding roads, and the crazy height differences, much like the game maps designed by the famous Japanese game designer Hidetaka Miyazaki (known for works like 'Sekiro'). If you're interested in Chongqing, I highly recommend checking out his videos—they're really fascinating!

Update: I just noticed that '重庆磊少' (Chongqing Lei Shao) has changed his Bilibili account name to '懂楼汇-磊少' (Dong Lou Hui - Lei Shao). I hope those who want to learn about Chongqing through his videos can search for his new name on Bilibili.

In most cases, when Chinese people use the word "nigga" (or something that sounds similar), they are not using it with the same meaning as in English. The Chinese phrase "nǐ gè" (你个) or "nèige" (那个), which means "you" or "that," can sound phonetically similar to the N-word in English. This sometimes causes misunderstandings, especially among non-Chinese speakers.

However, some younger Chinese people who are influenced by hip-hop culture might intentionally use the word "nigga" in the way it's used in rap music, often as slang for "bro" or "friend." This is usually done without fully understanding the history and impact of the word in Western culture.

If you saw or heard a Chinese person using it, the context is key. If it was in a casual conversation in Mandarin, it was likely just a misinterpretation of their normal speech. If it was in a hip-hop or online setting, they might be imitating Western slang without knowing its full meaning.
